  "prompt": "English Grammar: Is it 'Can you explain me?' or 'Could you explain me?'",
  "response": "The correct phrase is \"Can you explain to me?\" or \"Could you explain to me?\"\n\nIn English, when asking someone to explain something, you typically use the verb \"explain\" with the preposition \"to\" before the person you're asking.\n\nCorrect variations include:\n1. \"Can you explain this to me?\"\n2. \"Could you explain that to me?\"\n3. \"Would you explain the concept to me?\"\n\nIncorrect versions:\n- \"Can you explain me?\" (grammatically incorrect)\n- \"Could you explain me?\" (grammatically incorrect)\n\nThe key is to include \"to\" before the person receiving the explanation.",
